"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to their exponential forms:\n  - $x^{24} = w$\n  - $y^{40} = w$\n  - $(xyz)^{12} = w$\n\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 5 to make the exponents comparable:\n  - $x^{120} = w^5$\n  - $y^{120} = w^3$\n  - $(xyz)^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions for $x^{120}$ and $y^{120}$ into the equation for $(xyz)^{120}$:\n  - $w^5 \\cdot w^3 \\cdot z^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 4: Simplify the equation to isolate $z^{120}$:\n  - $z^{120} = w^{2}$\n\nStep 5: Take the logarithm base $z$ of both sides to find $\\log_z w$:\n  - $\\log_z w = 60$\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma showing that if $a > 1$ and $b > 0$, then $\\log_a b = c$ implies $a^c = b$.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_exponential_form:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a > 1\" and \"b > 0\"\n  shows \"ln b / ln a = c \\<longleftrightarrow> a ^ c = b\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma showing that if $a > 1$ and $b > 0$, then $(a^m)^n = a^{mn}$.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma power_of_power:\n  fixes a m n :: real\n  assumes \"a > 1\" and \"m > 0\" and \"n > 0\"\n  shows \"(a ^ m) ^ n = a ^ (m * n)\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma showing that if $a > 1$ and $b > 0$, then $\\log_a (b^n) = n \\log_a b$.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma log_power:\n  fixes a b n :: real\n  assumes \"a > 1\" and \"b > 0\" and \"n > 0\"\n  shows \"ln (b ^ n) / ln a = n * (ln b / ln a)\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\nThese lemmas will help in converting between logarithmic and exponential forms, and in manipulating the equations to isolate the desired quantity."